00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:43.030
Enough, my lord.

268
00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:46.730
My lord, I must confess Iknow this woman:

269
00:10:46.730 --> 00:10:48.000
And five years since therewas

270
00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:49.430
some speech of marriage

271
00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:52.000
Betwixt myself and her;which was broke off,

272
00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.300
Partly for that herpromised proportions

273
00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:54.970
Came short of composition,but in chief

274
00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:59.770
For that her reputationwas disvalued

275
00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:03.670
In levity: since whichtime of five years

276
00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:05.500
I never spake with her,saw her,

277
00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:06.270
nor heard from her,

278
00:11:06.270 --> 00:11:07.570
Upon my faith and honour.

279
00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:09.230
Noble prince,

280
00:11:09.230 --> 00:11:11.130
As there comes light fromheaven

281
00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:12.930
and words from breath,

282
00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:16.930
As there is sense in truthand truth in virtue,

283
00:11:16.930 --> 00:11:19.430
I am affianced this man'swife as strongly

284
00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:22.430
As words could make upvows:

285
00:11:22.430 --> 00:11:24.130
and, my good lord,

286
00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:27.800
But Tuesday night lastgone in's garden-house

287
00:11:27.800 --> 00:11:30.500
He knew me as a wife.

288
00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:31.500
As this is true,

289
00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:34.430
Let me in safety raise mefrom my knees

290
00:11:34.430 --> 00:11:37.100
Or else for ever beconfixed here,

291
00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:40.530
A marble monument!

292
00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:43.930
I did but smile till now:

293
00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:48.470
Now, good my lord, give methe scope of justice

294
00:11:48.470 --> 00:11:50.630
My patience here istouch'd.

295
00:11:50.630 --> 00:11:51.530
I do perceive

296
00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:52.970
These poor informal womenare no more

297
00:11:52.970 --> 00:11:54.600
But instruments of somemore mightier member

298
00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:57.170
That sets them on: let mehave way, my lord,

299
00:11:57.170 --> 00:11:58.730
To find this practise out.

300
00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:00.730
Ay, with my heart

301
00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:03.070
And punish them to yourheight of pleasure.

302
00:12:03.070 --> 00:12:04.970
Thou foolish friar,

303
00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:06.370
and thou pernicious woman,

304
00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:08.370
Compact with her that'sgone,

305
00:12:08.370 --> 00:12:10.030
think'st thou thy oaths,

306
00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:12.630
Though they would sweardown each particular saint,

307
00:12:12.630 --> 00:12:14.830
Were testimonies againsthis worth and credit

308
00:12:14.830 --> 00:12:18.770
That's seal'd in approbation?You, Lord Escalus,

309
00:12:18.770 --> 00:12:20.830
Sit with my cousin; lendhim your kind pains

310
00:12:20.830 --> 00:12:24.500
To find out this abuse,whence 'tis derived.

311
00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:25.730
There is another friarthat set them on;

312
00:12:25.730 --> 00:12:26.800
Let him be sent for.

313
00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:28.500
Would he were here, mylord! for he indeed

314
00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:30.000
Hath set the women on tothis complaint:

315
00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.970
Your provost knows theplace where he abides

316
00:12:32.970 --> 00:12:34.670
And he may fetch him.

317
00:12:34.670 --> 00:12:36.170
Go do it instantly.

318
00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:37.800
And you, my noble andwell-warranted cousin,

319
00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:40.070
Whom it concerns to hearthis matter forth,

320
00:12:40.070 --> 00:12:42.170
Do with your injuries asseems you best,

321
00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:45.030
In any chastisement: I fora while will leave you;

322
00:12:45.030 --> 00:12:48.500
But stir not you till youhave well determined

323
00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:51.170
Upon these slanderers.

324
00:12:51.170 --> 00:12:53.900
My lord, we'll do itthroughly.

325
00:12:54.430 --> 00:13:03.200
(applause)

326
00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:06.370
Signior Lucio, did not yousay you knew that

327
00:13:06.370 --> 00:13:08.930
Friar Lodowick to be adishonest person?

328
00:13:08.930 --> 00:13:12.130
'Cucullus non facitmonachum:'

329
00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:14.670
honest in nothing but inhis clothes;

330
00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:15.630
and one that hath spoke

331
00:13:15.630 --> 00:13:17.670
most villanous speeches ofthe duke.

332
00:13:17.670 --> 00:13:19.230
We shall entreat you toabide here

333
00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:22.700
till he come and enforcethem against him:

334
00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:24.530
we shall find this friar anotable fellow.

335
00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:27.030
As any in Vienna, on myword.

336
00:13:27.030 --> 00:13:28.900
Call that same Isabel hereonce again;

337
00:13:28.900 --> 00:13:31.270
I would speak with her.

338
00:13:31.270 --> 00:13:35.200
Pray you, my lord, give meleave to question;

339
00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:36.630
you shall see how I'llhandle her.

340
00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:38.900
Not better than he, by herown report.

341
00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:40.070
Say you?

342
00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:42.570
Marry, sir, I think, ifyou handled her privately,

343
00:13:42.570 --> 00:13:45.230
she would sooner confess:perchance, publicly,

344
00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:46.100
she'll be ashamed.

345
00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:48.070
I will go darkly to workwith her.

346
00:13:48.070 --> 00:13:54.570
That's the way; for womenare light at midnight.

347
00:13:54.570 --> 00:13:56.930
Come on, mistress:

348
00:13:56.930 --> 00:13:59.570
here's a gentlewoman deniesall that you have said.

349
00:13:59.570 --> 00:14:01.430
My lord, here comes therascal I spoke of;

350
00:14:01.430 --> 00:14:03.030
here with the provost.

351
00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:04.430
In very good time:

352
00:14:04.430 --> 00:14:06.100
speak not you to him tillwe call upon you.

353
00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:08.500
Mum.

354
00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:10.430
Come, sir: did you setthese women on

355
00:14:10.430 --> 00:14:12.570
to slander Lord Angelo?

356
00:14:12.570 --> 00:14:13.900
they have confessed youdid.

357
00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:15.600
'Tis false.

358
00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:16.900
How! know you where youare?

359
00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:19.130
Respect to your greatplace!

360
00:14:19.130 --> 00:14:20.170
and let the devil

361
00:14:20.170 --> 00:14:21.770
Be sometime honour'd forhis burning throne!

362
00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:23.470
Where is the duke? 'tis heshould hear me speak.

363
00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:26.730
The duke's in us; and wewill hear you speak:

364
00:14:26.730 --> 00:14:29.600
Look you speak justly.

365
00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:32.170
Boldly, at least. But, O,poor souls,

366
00:14:32.170 --> 00:14:34.530
Come you to seek the lambhere of the fox?

367
00:14:34.530 --> 00:14:38.370
Good night to yourredress! Is the duke gone?

368
00:14:38.370 --> 00:14:42.100
Then is your cause gonetoo.

369
00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:43.270
The duke's unjust,

370
00:14:43.270 --> 00:14:45.500
Thus to retort yourmanifest appeal,

371
00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:48.030
And put your trial in thevillain's mouth

372
00:14:48.030 --> 00:14:51.300
Which here you come toaccuse.

373
00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:53.630
This is the rascal; thisis he I spoke of.

374
00:14:53.630 --> 00:14:55.600
Why, thou unreverend andunhallow'd friar,

375
00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:57.700
Is't not enough thou hastsuborn'd these women

376
00:14:57.700 --> 00:14:59.500
To accuse this worthy man,

377
00:14:59.500 --> 00:15:01.400
but, in foul mouth

378
00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:02.970
And in the witness of hisproper ear,

379
00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:05.370
To call him villain?

380
00:15:05.370 --> 00:15:07.700
and then to glance fromhim to the duke himself,

381
00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:09.770
to tax him with injustice?

382
00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:12.370
Take him hence; to therack with him!

383
00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:14.500
We'll touse you joint byjoint,

384
00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:18.330
but we will know hispurpose. What 'unjust'!

385
00:15:18.330 --> 00:15:20.800
Be not so hot; the duke

386
00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:23.200
Dare no more stretch thisfinger of mine than he

387
00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:27.600
Dare rack his own: hissubject am I not,

388
00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:30.100
Nor here provincial.

389
00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:31.200
My business in this state

390
00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:34.200
Made me a looker on herein Vienna,

391
00:15:34.200 --> 00:15:36.430
Where I have seencorruption boil and bubble

392
00:15:36.430 --> 00:15:39.600
Till it o'er-run the stew;

393
00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:43.130
laws for all faults,

394
00:15:43.130 --> 00:15:45.470
But faults socountenanced,

395
00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:46.930
that the strong statutes

396
00:15:46.930 --> 00:15:49.430
Stand like the forfeits ina barber's shop,

397
00:15:49.430 --> 00:15:51.030
As much in mock as mark.

398
00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:55.200
Slander to the state! Awaywith him to prison!

399
00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.500
What can you vouch againsthim, Signior Lucio?

400
00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:58.870
Is this the man that youdid tell us of?

401
00:15:58.870 --> 00:16:01.100
'Tis he, my lord.

402
00:16:01.100 --> 00:16:05.570
Come hither, goodmanbaldpate:

403
00:16:05.570 --> 00:16:06.970
do you know me?

404
00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:08.370
I remember you, sir, bythe sound of your voice:

405
00:16:08.370 --> 00:16:09.300
I met you at the prison,

406
00:16:09.300 --> 00:16:10.700
in the absence of theduke.

407
00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:12.230
O, did you so?

408
00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:14.500
And do you remember whatyou said of the duke?

409
00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:16.300
Most notedly, sir.

410
00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:20.000
Do you so, sir? And wasthe duke a fleshmonger,

411
00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:21.970
a fool, and a coward,

412
00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:23.800
as you then reported himto be?

413
00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:25.930
You must, sir, changepersons with me,

414
00:16:25.930 --> 00:16:28.270
ere you make that myreport:

415
00:16:28.270 --> 00:16:29.900
for you sir, indeed,spoke of him;

416
00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:32.470
and much more, much worse.

417
00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:33.600
O thou damnable fellow!

418
00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:37.230
Did not I tweak thee bythe nose for thy speeches?

419
00:16:37.230 --> 00:16:40.330
I protest I love the dukeas I love myself.

420
00:16:40.330 --> 00:16:41.970
Hark, how the villainwould close now,

421
00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:43.930
after his treasonableabuses!

422
00:16:43.930 --> 00:16:46.130
Such a fellow is not to betalked withal.

423
00:16:46.130 --> 00:16:48.970
Away with him to prison!

424
00:16:48.970 --> 00:16:51.530
Where is the provost? Awaywith him to prison!

425
00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:54.200
lay bolts enough upon him:

426
00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:55.630
let him speak no more.

427
00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:57.500
Away with those giglotstoo,

428
00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:00.070
and with the otherconfederate companion!

429
00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:01.900
Stay, sir; stay awhile.

430
00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:04.030
What, resists he? Helphim, Lucio.

431
00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:07.570
Come, sir; come, sir;come, sir; foh, sir!

432
00:17:07.570 --> 00:17:11.270
Why, you bald-pated, lyingrascal,

433
00:17:11.270 --> 00:17:14.430
you must be hooded, mustyou?

434
00:17:14.430 --> 00:17:17.500
Show your knave's visage,with a pox to you!

435
00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:21.330
show your sheep-biting face,and be hanged an hour!

436
00:17:21.330 --> 00:17:25.930
Will't not off?

437
00:17:33.870 --> 00:17:34.870
Thou art the first knave

438
00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:37.070
that e'er madest a duke.

439
00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:39.170
First, provost, let mebail these gentle three.

440
00:17:39.170 --> 00:17:41.800
Sneak not away, sir; forthe friar and you

441
00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:44.570
Must have a word anon. Layhold on him.

442
00:17:44.570 --> 00:17:47.470
This may prove worse thanhanging.

443
00:17:47.470 --> 00:17:49.330
What you have spoke Ipardon: sit you down:

444
00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:53.500
We'll borrow place of him.

445
00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:03.530
Sir, by your leave.

446
00:18:03.530 --> 00:18:06.170
Hast thou or word, or wit,or impudence,

447
00:18:06.170 --> 00:18:08.570
That yet can do theeoffice? If thou hast,

448
00:18:08.570 --> 00:18:11.400
Rely upon it till my talebe told,

449
00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:14.230
And hold no longer out.

450
00:18:14.230 --> 00:18:16.130
O my dread lord,

451
00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:18.100
I should be guiltier thanmy guiltiness,

452
00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:19.470
To think I can beundiscernible,

453
00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:21.670
When I perceive yourgrace, like power divine,

454
00:18:21.670 --> 00:18:28.330
Hath look'd upon mypasses. Then, good prince,

455
00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:29.600
No longer session holdupon my shame,

456
00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:31.900
But let my trial be mineown confession:

457
00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:34.370
Immediate sentence thenand sequent death

458
00:18:34.370 --> 00:18:36.770
Is all the grace I beg.

459
00:18:36.770 --> 00:18:43.130
Come hither, Mariana.

460
00:18:43.130 --> 00:18:47.400
Say, wast thou e'ercontracted to this woman?

461
00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:49.500
I was, my lord.

462
00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:52.070
Go take her hence, andmarry her instantly.

463
00:18:52.070 --> 00:18:54.200
Do you the office, friar;which consummate,

464
00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:57.200
Return him here again. Gowith him, provost.

465
00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:11.170
My lord, I am more amazedat his dishonour

466
00:19:11.170 --> 00:19:13.930
Than at the strangeness ofit.

467
00:19:13.930 --> 00:19:16.700
Come hither, Isabel.

468
00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:25.770
Your friar is now yourprince: as I was then

469
00:19:25.770 --> 00:19:28.100
Advertising and holy toyour business,

470
00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:29.630
Not changing heart withhabit, I am still

471
00:19:29.630 --> 00:19:31.970
Attorney'd at yourservice.

472
00:19:31.970 --> 00:19:33.100
O, give me pardon,

473
00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:35.070
That I, your vassal, haveemploy'd and pain'd

474
00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:36.800
Your unknown sovereignty!

475
00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:38.730
You are pardon'd, Isabel:

476
00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:41.570
And now, dear maid, be youas free to us.

477
00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:44.530
Your brother's death, Iknow, sits at your heart;

478
00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:47.400
And you may marvel why Iobscured myself,

479
00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:50.070
Labouring to save hislife, and would not rather

480
00:19:50.070 --> 00:19:52.300
Make rash remonstrance ofmy hidden power

481
00:19:52.300 --> 00:19:55.470
Than let him so be lost. Omost kind maid,

482
00:19:55.470 --> 00:19:59.000
It was the swift celerityof his death,

483
00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:00.870
Which I did think withslower foot came on,

484
00:20:00.870 --> 00:20:04.700
That brain'd my purpose.But, peace be with him!

485
00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:07.070
That life is better life,past fearing death,

486
00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:09.730
Than that which lives tofear: make it your comfort,

487
00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:11.500
So happy is your brother.

488
00:20:11.500 --> 00:20:13.230
I do, my lord.

489
00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:18.100
For this new-married manapproaching here,

490
00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:20.230
Whose salt imagination yethath wrong'd

491
00:20:20.230 --> 00:20:23.170
Your well defended honour,you must pardon

492
00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:27.700
For Mariana's sake: but ashe adjudged your brother

493
00:20:27.700 --> 00:20:29.670
Being criminal, in doubleviolation

494
00:20:29.670 --> 00:20:33.270
Of sacred chastity and ofpromise-breach

495
00:20:33.270 --> 00:20:35.200
Thereon dependent, foryour brother's life,

496
00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:37.900
The very mercy of the lawcries out

497
00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:41.270
Most audible, even fromhis proper tongue,

498
00:20:41.270 --> 00:20:45.470
'An Angelo for Claudio,death for death!'

499
00:20:45.470 --> 00:20:47.030
Haste still pays haste,

500
00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:49.070
and leisure answersleisure;

501
00:20:49.070 --> 00:20:53.830
Like doth quit like, andMEASURE still FOR MEASURE.

502
00:20:53.830 --> 00:20:55.970
Thus, Angelo, your fault'sthus manifested;

503
00:20:55.970 --> 00:20:57.530
Which, though thou wouldstdeny,

504
00:20:57.530 --> 00:20:59.770
denies thee vantage.

505
00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:01.770
We do condemn thee to thevery block

506
00:21:01.770 --> 00:21:05.030
Where Claudio stoop'd todeath, and with like haste.

507
00:21:05.030 --> 00:21:05.970
Away with him!

508
00:21:05.970 --> 00:21:07.030
O my most gracious lord,

509
00:21:07.030 --> 00:21:09.070
I hope you will not mockme with a husband.

510
00:21:09.070 --> 00:21:11.230
It is your husband mock'dyou with a husband.

511
00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:13.330
Consenting to thesafeguard of your honour,

512
00:21:13.330 --> 00:21:16.170
I thought your marriagefit; else imputation,

513
00:21:16.170 --> 00:21:17.700
For that he knew you,might reproach your life

514
00:21:17.700 --> 00:21:19.870
And choke your good tocome;

515
00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:20.830
for his possessions,

516
00:21:20.830 --> 00:21:22.670
Although by confiscationthey are ours,

517
00:21:22.670 --> 00:21:24.370
We do instate and widowyou withal,

518
00:21:24.370 --> 00:21:25.670
To buy you a betterhusband.

519
00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:27.100
O my dear lord,

520
00:21:27.100 --> 00:21:29.200
I crave no other, nor nobetter man.

521
00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:31.030
Never crave him; we aredefinitive.

522
00:21:31.030 --> 00:21:31.970
Gentle my liege,--

523
00:21:31.970 --> 00:21:32.630
You do but lose yourlabour.

524
00:21:32.630 --> 00:21:33.770
Away with him to death!

525
00:21:33.770 --> 00:21:35.530
Now, sir, to you.

526
00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:40.230
O my good lord! SweetIsabel, take my part;

527
00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:42.230
Lend me your knees, andall my life to come

528
00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:45.700
I'll lend you all my lifeto do you service.

529
00:21:45.700 --> 00:21:48.670
